\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter, we look at unfinanced demand shocks.
 These are all classic demand shocks as described in the introduction.
 With the following mechanisms described in the introduction:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Initial shock directly or indirectly increases one or more demand components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased demand leads to increased sectoral production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased sectoral production leads to increased demand for production inputs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased demand for intermediate inputs raises imports and domestic sectoral
 output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased capital demand also raises imports and domestic sectoral output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased labor demand leads to increased wages, employment and labor supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased employment and wages leads to higher household income and increased
 demand for private consumption and housing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased housing demand leads to increased housing prices and housing investment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased housing prices and leverage allowed by mortgages lead to increased
 liquidity and additional household demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased production raises unit costs and pushes output prices up from
 the cost side
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Higher output prices lead to higher demand prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased demand prices dampen quantity demand over time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Full crowding out in employment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first shock we look at is a shock to government lump sum transfers to
 the households.
 Since financed shocks by default take place via lump sum transfers, an
 understanding of this shock is important in relation to all financed shocks.
 The other shocks are other demand shocks.
 Note that all shocks are unfinanced.
\end_layout

