\begin_layout Subsection
Govenment purchases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Government purchases of intermediate inputs are permanently increased by
 1 percent of baseline GDP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Government consumption and production increase through higher government
 purchases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main difference between this shock and the government employment shock
 is that here private production increases through intermediate inputs going
 into government production.
 The main input to government purchases is domestic input from the service
 sector.
 In the domestic service sector, increased production can be met by increased
 intermediate inputs, capital and labor, and in the short run also by increased
 factor utilization.
 This means employment needs to increase less in this shock since imports,
 capital, and in the short run utilization, can satisfy the need for increased
 production.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Negative effect on government budget and fiscal sustainability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Long run effect on GDP is positive as higher duties on government purchases
 than exports increase GDP for given GVA
\end_layout

