\begin_layout Subsection
Foreign demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The export market size is permanently increased, raising exports by 1 percent
 of baseline GDP for given prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Main shock is directly to exports that draw mostly on domestic manufacturing
 and services as well as import to re-exports of manufacturing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Positive effect on government budget and fiscal sustainability
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Short run effect on primary budget due to increased activity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Long run effect mainly due to interest revenue from initial surpluses
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Exports increase less than 1 percent in the short run due to rigidity and
 in the long run due to higher domestic wage and prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Positive long run effect on GDP as sea transport has a much larger export
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Sea transport has very little input of labor and domestic production so
 it is affected very little by higher wages.
 It does have capital input, which increases and makes long run GVA and
 GDP increase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is also a small effect from increased housing demand to increased
 capital and GVA in the housing sector
\end_layout

\end_deeper
